Phase 1 & Phase 2 analysis	Included
Execution authorization	Included
Re-inventing feasibility	Avoided
Re-arguing scope & failure tolerance	Avoided
Executive Comparison Summary
Path	Cost	Time	Risk
Build internally	$700k – $1.6M	9–24 months	High
License Mars Dust Trap	$5k	Immediate	Low (analysis already done)
Executive Interpretation

Licensing replaces ~$700,000 to $1,600,000 in early-phase internal spend with a $5,000 execution gate.

Analysis risk is already front-loaded and resolved.

Execution risk remains appropriately with the licensee.

This preserves capital for:

prototype fabrication

environmental testing

mission integration

operations

Instead of burning budget reinventing feasibility, framing, and justification work that has already been completed.

This is not a technology purchase.
This is a cost-avoidance, schedule-protection, and risk-reduction decision.

Plain-English Summary

Developing an equivalent Mars Dust Trap internally would likely cost $700k–$1.6M and take 9–24 months before producing usable hardware.
Licensing delivers immediate execution permission for $5,000, avoids early-phase reinvention, prevents scope drift, and preserves money for real engineering and testing instead of paperwork and feasibility rediscovery.
